snippet.textDisplay:
I am a tennis player who loves watching Djokovic play, enjoys his playful sense of humor, and respects his intelligence. I have long felt he is the best player in the world and have looked forward to teasing friends with a smiling  "I told you so"  when Djokovic surpasses Nadal and Federer for Grand Slam totals. 
However, even given all that, I support Australia's decision to send him home. 
The Serbians claim that he has somehow been horribly mistreated because he has been required to quarantine is nonsense. He has been required to do what many millions of less fortunate citizens around the world have been required to do for the sake of their fellow citizens. Except the likelihood is that he was held in much more luxurious hotels than they were. 
It appears that Djokovic's resistance to getting vaccinated may be part of a larger vulnerability he has to baseless and foolish conspiracy thinking (a recent article in a tennis magazine argued that persuasively). If that is the case, I hope that he can shake himself free of the damaging irrationality and soon return to the court. If so, I will be cheering for him. 
If I could talk with him I would say, "Nole, admitting you were wrong in public may be the hardest thing you have ever had to do. I had to do it when I was about your age. It's humiliating. I just hope you do seek informed opinion about the vaccination and work up the courage to change course.  
   --- David Gerstel, author of Paradise Incorporated and other books.
